ce:section.ce:para:
To further analyze the performance of the graphite/carbon dots nanobiosensor, its behaviour is modelled using a two-stage resistor–capacitor (RC) network, as illustrated in Fig. 9
                        . The first stage includes a parallel resistor and capacitor configuration that reflects the electrical characteristics of the graphite/carbon dots. In this model, RG/CDs denotes the total resistance of the printed graphite/carbon dots film, while CG/CDs represents the double-layer capacitance generated by surface charge distribution around the graphite/carbon dots. The second stage simulates the interaction between the sensor surface and biological elements (i.e. IL-8-antigens). The resistance arising from charge movement associated with biomolecular activity is modelled as Rct and the double layer capacitance formed at the interface between the graphite/carbon dots surface and the surrounding liquid is described by constant phase element (Yo). α is related to constant phase element and is less than 1 for imperfect capacitors. Additionally, the resistance offered by ions in the buffer solution is represented as Rs [44]. The experimental data achieved as a result of testing the biosensor against different concentrations of IL-8 were fitted with the parameters above. Rs is 14.529 kΩ, RG/CDs is 25 kΩ and CG/CDs s is 3.1213 μF. Yo, α and Rct were altered as the concentration of IL8 increased from 1 ng/mL to 10 μg/mL (see Table 1
                        ). The increase in Yo agrees with the increasing trend in capacitance observed in Fig. 8a. Changes in Yo and Rct can be attributed to different factors including change in dielectric constant at the surface, conformation of bound molecules or polarity. Furthermore, increased surface area due to antigen immobilization at the biosensor surface has significant impact on the impedimetric parameters of the biosensor [45,46]. The increase observed for α can be attributed to passivation of the surface with more IL-8 antigens which results in a more capacitive behaviour.
